WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:13.600
Good afternoon everyone, by good afternoon I of course mean good morning.

00:00:13.600 --> 00:00:18.680
My name is Jonathan McPherson, like she said, I am a software engineer on the RStudio IDE

00:00:18.680 --> 00:00:21.440
and today I'm going to talk to you about some of the new language features that we've built

00:00:21.440 --> 00:00:24.260
into RStudio 1.2.

00:00:24.260 --> 00:00:26.959
Before I do that though, a bit of background.

00:00:26.959 --> 00:00:31.420
So it's been our experience that as people work with R, they are often working with more

00:00:31.420 --> 00:00:36.720
than one tool at the same time and they're creating projects that have bits and pieces

00:00:36.720 --> 00:00:39.040
that are composed of different languages.

00:00:39.040 --> 00:00:44.279
For example, if you're working with an R project in RStudio, you might need to get some data

00:00:44.279 --> 00:00:49.240
from a SQL database and so you need to open up another window to create a SQL query and

00:00:49.240 --> 00:00:55.160
look at the data there so you can analyze it in R and perhaps by the time you're done

00:00:55.160 --> 00:00:59.639
with this query, you think of the fine work that Wes McKinnon did on Pandas and think

00:00:59.639 --> 00:01:04.559
maybe you'll use that to analyze the data so you open up PyCharm and then you remember

00:01:04.559 --> 00:01:08.760
that you've actually been asked to visualize this data in a bubble chart which you can't

00:01:08.760 --> 00:01:13.160
think of an R package to do so you start visualizing that in D3 and then you start thinking about

00:01:13.160 --> 00:01:18.160
modeling and you start browsing Wikipedia for modeling languages like Stan and then

00:01:18.160 --> 00:01:21.000
you play that game on Wikipedia, have you ever played that game where you click on the

00:01:21.000 --> 00:01:25.519
very first link of every article and you always wind up at philosophy?

00:01:25.519 --> 00:01:26.519
Every time.

00:01:26.519 --> 00:01:27.879
Try it out.

00:01:27.879 --> 00:01:33.879
And then the next thing you know, you're at the zoo and you are shaving a yak.

00:01:33.879 --> 00:01:36.120
So this is, this will not do.

00:01:36.120 --> 00:01:39.360
So this is the kind of problem, one of the kinds of problems we are trying to solve with

00:01:39.360 --> 00:01:42.160
RStudio 1.2.

00:01:42.160 --> 00:01:46.680
So our goals for RStudio 1.2 are many but one of them is to be a more comprehensive

00:01:46.680 --> 00:01:49.360
workbench for your R projects.

00:01:49.360 --> 00:01:53.239
So we're going to embrace some of the languages that we commonly see people use in their R

00:01:53.239 --> 00:01:58.040
data science projects and we're going to make the interoperability between those languages

00:01:58.040 --> 00:02:01.040
a lot more seamless so that you're not doing so much context switching.

00:02:01.040 --> 00:02:04.040
If you think about that slide that I just showed with all those windows, like every

00:02:04.040 --> 00:02:08.360
time you have to switch between tools, switch between windows, every time you have to import

00:02:08.360 --> 00:02:13.039
data from one tool, export it into another tool, that takes a lot of your time and mental

00:02:13.039 --> 00:02:16.759
energy and kind of breaks you out of the state of flow while you're working on your data

00:02:16.759 --> 00:02:17.960
science project.

00:02:17.960 --> 00:02:21.399
So we're hoping that we can take some of these workflows and make them really easy

00:02:21.399 --> 00:02:23.800
to do seamlessly right inside of RStudio.

00:02:23.800 --> 00:02:26.080
We also have some non-goals.

00:02:26.080 --> 00:02:28.479
We don't want to make one of these things.

00:02:28.479 --> 00:02:31.039
We are not trying to become a general purpose IDE.

00:02:31.039 --> 00:02:35.759
We're not trying to fully replace your dedicated tools or lose focus on R.

00:02:35.759 --> 00:02:40.520
So RStudio is and always will be first and foremost a workbench for data science with

00:02:40.520 --> 00:02:42.199
R.

00:02:42.199 --> 00:02:44.880
So here are our agenda.

00:02:44.880 --> 00:02:46.520
We're going to cover just a few languages.

00:02:46.520 --> 00:02:56.880
They are as follows, SQL, Python, we'll do D3, we'll do Stan, and if we have time at

00:02:56.880 --> 00:02:59.880
the end, I'm going to show you a couple of the other fun things we've added to RStudio

00:02:59.880 --> 00:03:00.880
1.2.

00:03:00.880 --> 00:03:01.880
All right.

00:03:01.880 --> 00:03:05.080
So for most of the rest of this talk, I'm just going to do a live demo of some of these

00:03:05.080 --> 00:03:08.279
new language features in RStudio, and I'm going to start with SQL.

00:03:08.279 --> 00:03:11.759
This will look pretty familiar if you went to the keynote this morning.

00:03:11.759 --> 00:03:17.080
So one of the things that we built into RStudio is a data connectivity, and here I'm connecting

00:03:17.080 --> 00:03:20.039
to a database for a record store.

00:03:20.039 --> 00:03:24.240
For those of you who still remember what a record store is.

00:03:24.240 --> 00:03:28.639
So this database has information about all of the records that we sell, all the artists

00:03:28.639 --> 00:03:33.199
who made those records, that is information about customers, our employees, how much people

00:03:33.199 --> 00:03:35.720
have paid for the records, et cetera.

00:03:35.720 --> 00:03:41.199
So I'm going to start out by creating a simple SQL query report that tells me all of the

00:03:41.199 --> 00:03:45.399
albums that I sell and which artists created those albums.

00:03:45.399 --> 00:03:48.880
As you can see, this data is currently in separate tables.

00:03:48.880 --> 00:03:53.080
So I'm going to start by pressing this new SQL button you'll see here.

00:03:53.080 --> 00:03:59.399
And we'll call this Albums, okay, and you'll notice right away that RStudio has suddenly

00:03:59.399 --> 00:04:03.360
become an interface that should be pretty familiar to anyone who has spent time working

00:04:03.360 --> 00:04:04.360
on SQL queries.

00:04:04.360 --> 00:04:08.479
Notice I have a list of tables over here, I have a query over here, and then I have

00:04:08.479 --> 00:04:10.839
the results of the query right here.

00:04:10.839 --> 00:04:15.479
And it's quite easy for me to work on the query and to get real-time feedback about

00:04:15.479 --> 00:04:18.320
the results of the query here.

00:04:18.320 --> 00:04:21.679
All right.

00:04:21.679 --> 00:04:25.119
So I just selected from the artist table as well.

00:04:25.119 --> 00:04:28.720
As you can see, this has a Cartesian join result, which is not at all what I want for

00:04:28.720 --> 00:04:29.880
this query.

00:04:29.880 --> 00:04:32.839
So I'm going to add a where clause.

00:04:32.839 --> 00:04:39.239
And you'll notice that as I'm typing, I'm getting real-time autocompletion of the results

00:04:39.640 --> 00:04:40.760
of the fields in the tables.

00:04:40.760 --> 00:04:51.119
So I can say where albums, and I can get autocompletion there to artist ID equals artists.artistID.

00:04:51.119 --> 00:04:52.119
And there we go.

00:04:52.119 --> 00:04:55.519
So now I've got a quick little SQL report that tells me all of the albums that I sell

00:04:55.519 --> 00:04:57.119
and all the artists who made the albums.

00:04:57.119 --> 00:05:01.980
Again, fairly straightforward, but really easy and very fluid for me to do this without

00:05:01.980 --> 00:05:06.799
opening 12 windows to look at my schema and my database and my results.

00:05:06.799 --> 00:05:11.720
The next thing that we're going to do is we are going to look at a little notebook

00:05:11.720 --> 00:05:13.720
that I've created.

00:05:13.720 --> 00:05:16.760
So this is a notebook that does a little bit more in-depth analysis.

00:05:16.760 --> 00:05:21.160
It's going to help me figure out who the top customers are at my failing record shop so

00:05:21.160 --> 00:05:25.040
I can figure out how I can get more money out of them.

00:05:25.040 --> 00:05:30.079
To start off with, we're just going to connect to the SQL database, and I'm going to use

00:05:30.079 --> 00:05:31.079
the reticulate package.

00:05:31.079 --> 00:05:37.279
Now, a lot of the things you're about to see are a direct result of the reticulate package.

00:05:37.279 --> 00:05:40.040
This package doesn't require our studio to use.

00:05:40.040 --> 00:05:44.600
It was put together by JJ and Kevin, and it powers a lot of the Python interoperability

00:05:44.600 --> 00:05:46.399
stuff you're about to see.

00:05:46.399 --> 00:05:50.000
But before we get to the Python stuff, I wanted to note that all of the really nice things

00:05:50.000 --> 00:05:54.679
that I just showed you are not only in the SQL window.

00:05:54.679 --> 00:05:58.720
They are also available to you inside of our markdown documents.

00:05:59.079 --> 00:06:05.440
Here I have a SQL query, and what this query does is it simply goes out and gets me a list

00:06:05.440 --> 00:06:11.260
of every customer and every invoice that that customer has ever had.

00:06:11.260 --> 00:06:13.959
So all that nice stuff that I just showed you is still available, right?

00:06:13.959 --> 00:06:19.760
So I can get the same kind of auto-completion that I'm used to.

00:06:19.760 --> 00:06:25.880
And I actually want to save this query into an output variable so I can use it later.

00:06:25.880 --> 00:06:26.880
So now I'm going to use Pandas.

00:06:27.880 --> 00:06:30.880
I'm going to use Pandas to summarize the data that I just created.

00:06:30.880 --> 00:06:35.160
So I made a list of invoices, now I'm going to use Pandas to group together and summarize

00:06:35.160 --> 00:06:39.160
that data to figure out who has spent the most total money on invoices.

00:06:39.160 --> 00:06:42.200
Let's go ahead and run that.

00:06:42.200 --> 00:06:46.440
And you can see here are my top five customers.

00:06:46.440 --> 00:06:49.920
Now I wanted to show you about a couple of things that you can do while you're authoring

00:06:49.920 --> 00:06:51.519
these chunks.

00:06:51.519 --> 00:06:55.480
First of all, you get the same kind of auto-completion you do in R. So just like you can type library

00:06:55.480 --> 00:07:01.160
R in R and you can get a list of your R packages, you can type import in a Python chunk, you'll

00:07:01.160 --> 00:07:04.399
get a list of your Python packages.

00:07:04.399 --> 00:07:10.600
You also get the same kind of method completion that you get inside of R. So for instance,

00:07:10.600 --> 00:07:14.799
we've got variables, we can see the names of the functions here.

00:07:14.799 --> 00:07:20.760
If we use a function, we can actually get help for that function right in the help pane.

00:07:20.760 --> 00:07:24.440
You can jump to the definition of that function right in its Python file.

00:07:24.440 --> 00:07:30.320
So we think that these capabilities will make it really easy for you to very fluidly

00:07:30.320 --> 00:07:35.200
and naturally author Python chunks inside of R Markdown or other bits and pieces of

00:07:35.200 --> 00:07:36.200
your R project.

00:07:36.200 --> 00:07:41.079
The other thing I'd like to point out here, and some of you who are a little bit more

00:07:41.079 --> 00:07:46.399
astute might have already noticed it, is that I didn't have to do anything to get that data

00:07:46.399 --> 00:07:49.519
from SQL into my Python chunk.

00:07:49.519 --> 00:07:50.519
And the reason is this.

00:07:50.519 --> 00:07:55.600
Notice that when I created an output variable here in SQL, it went into my global environment

00:07:55.600 --> 00:07:56.600
right here.

00:07:56.600 --> 00:07:59.640
See, here's that data from SQL.

00:07:59.640 --> 00:08:05.720
And the only thing I needed to do to reference that data in Python is this.

00:08:05.720 --> 00:08:06.720
R.spinning.

00:08:06.720 --> 00:08:10.799
That just takes the variable from R called spinning and allows me to use it right inside

00:08:10.799 --> 00:08:15.519
my Python code.

00:08:15.519 --> 00:08:22.160
In previous versions of RStudio and R Markdown, Python chunks basically ran in a vacuum.

00:08:22.160 --> 00:08:25.720
You had to import the data at the beginning of the chunk from wherever and save it at

00:08:25.720 --> 00:08:26.720
the end.

00:08:26.720 --> 00:08:28.440
And that's no longer necessary.

00:08:28.440 --> 00:08:32.039
Reticulate actually embeds a Python session inside of your R session.

00:08:32.039 --> 00:08:35.320
So it's very easy and seamless to get data in and out of Python.

00:08:35.320 --> 00:08:41.039
Speaking of getting data in and out of Python, it's also quite easy to do the opposite of

00:08:41.039 --> 00:08:42.200
what I just showed you.

00:08:42.200 --> 00:08:47.960
Just like you can say R dot in Python, you can say pi dollar sign in R, notice here I'm

00:08:47.960 --> 00:08:54.919
getting a nice realtime autocompletion that not only tells me what data from Python is

00:08:54.919 --> 00:08:58.159
available but also gives me some information about that data.

00:08:58.159 --> 00:09:04.520
So it's here I can run that chunk and now I've got the summarized data from Python.

00:09:04.520 --> 00:09:06.200
Now let's do a little bit of visualization.

00:09:06.200 --> 00:09:08.440
This is something you also kind of saw hinted at in the keynote.

00:09:09.440 --> 00:09:15.559
I'm going to use Matplotlib again right inside of R studio to visualize these top five spinners

00:09:15.559 --> 00:09:19.559
at my fancy record shop.

00:09:19.559 --> 00:09:25.039
Now another thing I want you to notice here is that each one of these Python chunks is

00:09:25.039 --> 00:09:28.200
running in the same Python session.

00:09:28.200 --> 00:09:33.559
In previous versions you basically had to run each Python session independently.

00:09:33.559 --> 00:09:38.479
Every one of these chunks would start a new Python session, run all of the code, and then

00:09:38.479 --> 00:09:39.479
quit.

00:09:39.479 --> 00:09:42.919
So now that we have an embedded session, these things can build on each other.

00:09:42.919 --> 00:09:48.159
You can actually, just like you can with R chunks, you can build seamlessly chunk to

00:09:48.159 --> 00:09:53.039
chunk inside of your Python chunks.

00:09:53.039 --> 00:09:58.119
So the last chunk in this notebook is a D3 visualization.

00:09:58.119 --> 00:10:02.359
So it's basically going to take that same data.

00:10:02.359 --> 00:10:07.559
And I'm going to sort by the number of people here and there we go.

00:10:07.559 --> 00:10:11.479
I made a nice little bubble chart.

00:10:11.479 --> 00:10:15.159
So I want you to notice here that R studio is not only, you know, an environment where

00:10:15.159 --> 00:10:20.159
you can look at these D3 visualizations, it's also an environment where you can create them.

00:10:20.159 --> 00:10:26.080
So you'll notice here that this bubble chart that I made is a D3 script called bubbles.js

00:10:26.080 --> 00:10:31.559
and I can just open that and start working on that visualization.

00:10:31.559 --> 00:10:34.239
You'll notice I've got a preview button here so I can take a look at what this visualization

00:10:34.239 --> 00:10:35.840
looks like.

00:10:35.840 --> 00:10:39.400
And I think you'll notice that the font is really a little bit too small here.

00:10:39.400 --> 00:10:40.960
So let's go ahead and bump that up.

00:10:40.960 --> 00:10:45.559
Notice, again, there's some sample data up here so that I don't have to have any actual

00:10:45.559 --> 00:10:47.599
live data connected to this thing to work with it.

00:10:47.599 --> 00:10:49.159
Let's go ahead and preview it.

00:10:49.159 --> 00:10:51.359
You can see the font's slightly more reasonable.

00:10:51.359 --> 00:10:56.599
And if I go back here and run my visualization, you'll see that now my customer's names are

00:10:56.599 --> 00:10:57.979
a lot easier to see.

00:10:57.979 --> 00:11:06.739
So again, very seamless authoring and integration of D3 visualizations inside of R studio.

00:11:06.739 --> 00:11:10.099
So now that we've kind of taken a look at our top five spenders and spent a little bit

00:11:10.099 --> 00:11:14.619
of time kind of passing data back and forth, I want you to take a step back and think about

00:11:14.619 --> 00:11:15.859
what we've just done here.

00:11:15.859 --> 00:11:22.619
We've brought together SQL and R and Python and D3 into a reproducible publishable report

00:11:22.619 --> 00:11:24.260
all without leaving R studio.

00:11:25.260 --> 00:11:28.820
It's really our hope that it's going to be very easy for you to compose these same kinds

00:11:28.820 --> 00:11:31.979
of multi-language workflows yourself.

00:11:31.979 --> 00:11:34.619
So there's a couple other Python features I wanted to show you really quickly while

00:11:34.619 --> 00:11:36.820
we're talking about it.

00:11:36.820 --> 00:11:38.179
Python.

00:11:38.179 --> 00:11:44.419
And that is mainly that there's a couple things that you can do in Python that are only possible

00:11:44.419 --> 00:11:45.739
in Python scripts.

00:11:45.739 --> 00:11:48.219
So you'll notice here I have a new source script button.

00:11:48.219 --> 00:11:52.299
This just runs the same code that we looked at earlier that analyzes my top five spenders.

00:11:52.940 --> 00:11:56.780
However, it's not only possible for me to run the whole script at once, but just like

00:11:56.780 --> 00:12:00.859
you can in R, you can run the script one line at a time.

00:12:00.859 --> 00:12:06.500
And you'll notice that when I do that, R studio automatically switches to an embedded Python

00:12:06.500 --> 00:12:07.500
console.

00:12:07.500 --> 00:12:12.380
And this is also powered by the reticulate package and it uses that same embedded R sorry,

00:12:12.380 --> 00:12:15.559
that same embedded Python session that the chunks were using.

00:12:15.559 --> 00:12:18.380
So all of my state is still here.

00:12:18.380 --> 00:12:22.500
And it's very easy for me to iterate on it and I can, you know, type my own Python code

00:12:22.500 --> 00:12:24.460
if I want to.

00:12:24.460 --> 00:12:25.460
And there we go.

00:12:25.460 --> 00:12:26.460
All right.

00:12:26.460 --> 00:12:31.380
So the only language we haven't talked about is Stan.

00:12:31.380 --> 00:12:33.580
I'm not going to spend a whole lot of time on it.

00:12:33.580 --> 00:12:39.099
But for those of you who have worked with Stan, we've now made Stan quite a lot easier

00:12:39.099 --> 00:12:40.099
to work with.

00:12:40.099 --> 00:12:42.979
We've got a very dedicated editor mode for it now.

00:12:42.979 --> 00:12:47.859
We have all the same things that I just showed you with respect to Python and SQL.

00:12:47.859 --> 00:12:48.859
You also will get in Stan.

00:12:48.859 --> 00:12:49.859
So you have auto completion.

00:12:49.859 --> 00:12:54.299
You can see here I've got a list of all the functions I can call.

00:12:54.299 --> 00:13:04.460
You'll notice I've already created a syntax error, which is right there.

00:13:04.460 --> 00:13:09.059
And we also have a document outline that makes it really easy for you to navigate your Stan

00:13:09.059 --> 00:13:10.059
code.

00:13:10.059 --> 00:13:12.940
I'm not a Stan expert, so I'm not going to spend a lot more time on this, but we hope

00:13:12.940 --> 00:13:16.859
this makes it a lot easier for you to work with Stan projects inside of the IDE.

00:13:16.859 --> 00:13:18.900
All right.

00:13:18.900 --> 00:13:24.419
So with our last five minutes or so, I want to show you a couple of other small features

00:13:24.419 --> 00:13:26.700
we've added to RStudio 1.2.

00:13:26.700 --> 00:13:30.380
So the first of these is background jobs.

00:13:30.380 --> 00:13:34.500
So it's been our experience that when people work with R, they will often create R scripts

00:13:34.500 --> 00:13:37.140
that really take quite a lot of time to run.

00:13:37.140 --> 00:13:40.539
And if you've ever had to work with these inside of RStudio, you know that you basically

00:13:40.539 --> 00:13:43.580
have to run the script and then wait.

00:13:43.580 --> 00:13:48.140
Because you can't do a whole lot of things with RStudio while the R session is busy.

00:13:48.140 --> 00:13:52.460
If you're on RStudio desktop, you can launch another copy of RStudio to get some other

00:13:52.460 --> 00:13:54.260
possibly unrelated work done.

00:13:54.260 --> 00:13:58.940
But it can be quite challenging if you want to run a couple of these things.

00:13:58.940 --> 00:14:04.599
So a background job is basically just running an R script or something like it inside a

00:14:04.599 --> 00:14:06.280
background R task.

00:14:06.280 --> 00:14:08.500
So we've got a new button here called sources local job.

00:14:08.500 --> 00:14:14.260
And that's just going to take the script that I wrote and run it in the background.

00:14:14.260 --> 00:14:15.260
And get me some results when I'm done.

00:14:15.260 --> 00:14:19.739
I'm going to copy the results to the global environment and go ahead and start the job.

00:14:19.739 --> 00:14:23.299
You'll notice here that I get progress and output for the job as it runs.

00:14:23.299 --> 00:14:25.219
I've got a list of running jobs over here.

00:14:25.219 --> 00:14:26.859
I can monitor them in the console.

00:14:26.859 --> 00:14:31.460
And while the job is running, all of the things that RStudio does are still available.

00:14:31.460 --> 00:14:33.739
So the R session is not busy.

00:14:33.739 --> 00:14:37.900
And I'm able to continue to do work while I run these background processes.

00:14:37.900 --> 00:14:39.440
You're not limited to just one job.

00:14:39.440 --> 00:14:42.700
You can run multiple jobs at once.

00:14:42.700 --> 00:14:46.900
It is possible to run as many jobs as your machine has the capacity for.

00:14:46.900 --> 00:14:52.099
So hopefully this will make it a lot easier for you to take those long running computations

00:14:52.099 --> 00:14:59.539
and make them work really nicely without, again, having to constantly switch contexts.

00:14:59.539 --> 00:15:05.580
The next little thing that I wanted to show is auto installation of missing R packages.

00:15:05.900 --> 00:15:09.059
This is another quality of life improvement that we've made.

00:15:09.059 --> 00:15:13.820
And we've noticed when people open up an R script that they themselves wrote a long time

00:15:13.820 --> 00:15:18.419
ago or from another coworker and they don't have the right packages installed, it's kind

00:15:18.419 --> 00:15:19.419
of a pain.

00:15:19.419 --> 00:15:24.340
You have to go manually find the packages that are missing and manually install them.

00:15:24.340 --> 00:15:28.080
It sometimes takes a couple of times to run the script to figure out which packages you

00:15:28.080 --> 00:15:29.739
actually need.

00:15:29.739 --> 00:15:38.099
So in RStudio 1.2, we have created a code parser that basically analyzes your code

00:15:38.099 --> 00:15:42.580
to figure out what packages you're going to need in order to run the script and then gives

00:15:42.580 --> 00:15:46.859
you a little prompt that offers to install those packages for you.

00:15:46.859 --> 00:15:50.979
You'll notice here that I have asked to run an R script that uses the carrot package and

00:15:50.979 --> 00:15:54.140
the ML package.

00:15:54.140 --> 00:15:57.500
Because I don't actually have those packages installed, it's going to actually offer to

00:15:57.500 --> 00:16:04.619
install them for me.

00:16:04.619 --> 00:16:08.500
One other little quality of life improvement that we've added is the ability to create

00:16:08.500 --> 00:16:09.500
PowerPoint presentations.

00:16:09.500 --> 00:16:16.580
I'm not going to spend a whole lot of time on this, but a lot of people just for purposes

00:16:16.580 --> 00:16:22.700
of, you know, getting their workflow done, like, their R stuff winds up in a PowerPoint

00:16:22.700 --> 00:16:23.700
presentation.

00:16:23.700 --> 00:16:26.299
So you can now make those very easily.

00:16:26.299 --> 00:16:31.260
It's just as easy as making a Word document with R Markdown.

00:16:31.260 --> 00:16:37.820
And finally, I wanted to show you the appearances pane here.

00:16:37.820 --> 00:16:41.059
So we've also made it really easy to change RStudio's colors.

00:16:41.059 --> 00:16:45.299
This is another small quality of life improvement that people have been asking us for for many

00:16:45.299 --> 00:16:47.359
years.

00:16:47.359 --> 00:16:52.219
And it basically makes it possible for you to add or remove your own custom themes.

00:16:52.219 --> 00:16:54.820
You can make these themes yourself online.

00:16:54.820 --> 00:16:57.859
It's possible to do them with any text theme editor.

00:16:57.859 --> 00:17:00.820
And we have our own theme format, too, if you need further tweaking.

00:17:00.820 --> 00:17:02.539
Particularly like this theme that somebody made for us.

00:17:02.539 --> 00:17:08.099
It's a Christmas theme, and it has a candy cane background for your cursor line.

00:17:08.099 --> 00:17:11.140
So that's pretty fun.

00:17:11.140 --> 00:17:13.420
All right.

00:17:13.420 --> 00:17:16.260
So I just have a few minutes left, so let's wrap it up.

00:17:16.260 --> 00:17:17.500
We did the demo.

00:17:17.500 --> 00:17:21.780
So in summary, we hope that the 1.2 release makes it a lot more seamless for you to work

00:17:21.780 --> 00:17:25.699
with your data science projects that span languages and technologies.

00:17:25.699 --> 00:17:28.060
We've added a whole bunch of quality of life improvements.

00:17:28.060 --> 00:17:29.619
You can do background jobs.

00:17:29.619 --> 00:17:31.859
You can install packages that you don't have automatically.

00:17:31.859 --> 00:17:33.099
We have custom themes.

00:17:33.099 --> 00:17:34.380
There's a whole bunch of other stuff.

00:17:34.380 --> 00:17:38.420
I'm glossing over large swaths of improvements here.

00:17:38.420 --> 00:17:43.660
And all the stuff that you're seeing today is available in RStudio 1.2 public preview,

00:17:43.660 --> 00:17:49.760
which is getting quite close to a stable release, which we expect to have out this spring.

00:17:49.760 --> 00:17:54.160
And if you want to get at any of the code that I've shown in this presentation, I've

00:17:54.160 --> 00:17:55.920
put it up at this link.

00:17:55.920 --> 00:17:57.560
It's got everything that you need to run it.

00:17:57.560 --> 00:18:02.760
All you need to do is download the RStudio 1.2 preview, which I have linked at this as

00:18:02.760 --> 00:18:05.479
well, and you can run all that code yourself.

00:18:05.479 --> 00:18:06.479
All the data is included.

00:18:06.479 --> 00:18:11.280
So if you'd like to play with it and kind of get a feel for how working with those languages

00:18:11.280 --> 00:18:16.680
is, you're more than welcome to do so.

00:18:16.680 --> 00:18:17.680
And that's all I got.

00:18:17.680 --> 00:18:18.680
Thank you very much for your time.

00:18:18.680 --> 00:18:19.680
Thank you, Jonathan.

00:18:19.680 --> 00:18:32.359
We have time for a few questions while the next speaker is setting up.

00:18:32.359 --> 00:18:35.359
Just wave me down, and I'll throw this in your direction.

00:18:35.359 --> 00:18:51.680
Yeah, thanks for the great talk, Jonathan.

00:18:51.680 --> 00:18:56.640
For those background jobs, can you launch them on a compute cluster besides running

00:18:56.640 --> 00:18:59.040
them locally like you were doing there?

00:18:59.040 --> 00:19:02.640
Like any external R server or things like that?

00:19:02.640 --> 00:19:03.640
Got it.

00:19:03.640 --> 00:19:09.560
So the question was, you may have been sort of hinted into this by the fact that it says

00:19:09.560 --> 00:19:11.880
run local job.

00:19:11.880 --> 00:19:17.400
So there's a feature in RStudio server pro that allows you to run these jobs basically

00:19:17.400 --> 00:19:20.280
anywhere that your R sessions can run.

00:19:20.280 --> 00:19:24.280
If you're interested in learning more about that, there's a talk about the RStudio job

00:19:24.280 --> 00:19:28.719
launcher that will go into a lot more detail about how you can use the background jobs

00:19:28.719 --> 00:19:32.920
feature to launch much bigger jobs on your compute cluster.

00:19:32.920 --> 00:19:35.199
One more question?

00:19:35.199 --> 00:19:36.199
Yeah.

00:19:36.199 --> 00:19:43.959
Are there any plans to open up the languages to user-created highlighting and completion

00:19:43.959 --> 00:19:46.199
and stuff like that?

00:19:46.199 --> 00:19:50.520
So the question was, are we going to basically create a system that allows you to plug your

00:19:50.520 --> 00:19:58.119
own language engines into RStudio so that there's a possibility to make user extensible

00:19:58.119 --> 00:19:59.119
languages?

00:19:59.119 --> 00:20:02.760
We don't currently have plans for that, but we are watching the language server protocol

00:20:02.760 --> 00:20:07.560
project which Microsoft started for Visual Studio code that aims to provide a consistent

00:20:07.560 --> 00:20:09.219
back end for that kind of thing.

00:20:09.219 --> 00:20:14.119
So we're keeping an eye on it, but we don't have specific plans for it right now.

00:20:14.119 --> 00:20:15.119
Thank you.

00:20:15.119 --> 00:20:16.119
Oh, wait.

00:20:16.119 --> 00:20:17.119
30 seconds.

00:20:17.119 --> 00:20:18.119
I can answer a question in 30 seconds.

00:20:18.119 --> 00:20:19.119
Go ahead.

00:20:19.119 --> 00:20:20.119
Quickly.

00:20:20.119 --> 00:20:26.800
The package installation, will it look for GitHub as well or just CRAN packages?

00:20:26.800 --> 00:20:28.000
It only looks at CRAN packages.

00:20:28.000 --> 00:20:34.040
So when you open up an R script, there's really no way of telling where the package came from.

00:20:34.040 --> 00:20:36.959
So it's not looking for installation commands.

00:20:36.959 --> 00:20:39.319
It's looking for, like, library commands.

00:20:39.319 --> 00:20:43.520
So because it doesn't really know where the packages came from, all it can do is offer

00:20:43.520 --> 00:20:45.359
to install the CRAN versions.

00:20:45.359 --> 00:20:52.880
Now, that said, it is also pretty simple to use something like PackRat, and we're also

00:20:52.880 --> 00:20:56.920
working on a few other initiatives that will make it easier for you to snapshot your package

00:20:56.920 --> 00:20:59.520
dependencies and replay them on someone else's machine.

00:20:59.520 --> 00:21:03.959
So if you really care about, like, installing the exact version of the package that worked

00:21:03.959 --> 00:21:09.839
with R script, you need some other metadata of some kind.

00:21:09.839 --> 00:21:11.920
We don't currently support those for that particular feature.

